metadata.name: Glossolalia #187
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It‚Äôs less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù to the url to double the size, ‚Äú&density=3‚Äù to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append ‚Äú&grain=##‚Äù to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Paysages Chromatiques A #4
metadata.description:
Taking my inspiration from impressionist and contemporary paintings, I tried to generate 
mixtures of more or less superimposed colors, creating flowing effects or spots as one
would obtain with paint.
This work is the first in a two-part series featuring abstraction and imagination.
I hope it will inspire you to take the time to daydream, or simply to spend a moment 
where the mind can wander freely through the colors.

To save a png file type [s]
TO remove the texture type [t]

To render at higher resolution add &pd=2 at the end of the url in live mode
(others values are valid too but be patient the rendering can be long)
---
100% code made with p5js and glsl
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
---

metadata.name: partition() #163
metadata.description:
This token continuously partitions the canvas, sometimes taking minutes to create tens of thousands of subdivisions. Each token has unique properties that govern partition number and shape, and a random chance to freeze a partition. This allows for a wide variety of outputs, all driven by pure randomness.

Properties describe the entropy of the final output, the final number of partitions, and a rare small chance for filled partitions. This token also has a few interactive features as well (see below).

Software | p5.js
Created  | 11/30/21
Artist   | nicthib

Controls:
1-9: Displays the construction of the piece at each iteration
p: Save a png of the current canvas
s: Save an svg of the current canvas (Note: this can break the live sketch, so reload the page if you want to interact further)
Space: Resets animation
Scroll, click/drag: zoom/pan

metadata.name: Meander River Plot v1 #97
metadata.description:
A river meandering over a noise-based landscape. A line is drawn either horizontally, vertically, or more rarely, a ring. Time progresses for 1,000 iterations as the line travels, bends, and splits. 

There is a lot of variation on the line quality - from thin and controlled, to chunky and chaotic. It's a lot of fun to watch it run and see where it ends up.

I've been experimenting with this algorithm for a long time and this is the most visually interesting variation so far.

metadata.name: Gold in Your Eyes #36
metadata.description:
This piece came to be as an adaptation of a workflow developed for an earlier Blender series, DeVoids.

The idea behind this technique is, instead of trying to create an image that fits to the needs, to modify and distort the UV Mapping of a 3d model.

UV Maps are usually though of as a needed step in creating a 3d asset, where you must achieve minimal distortion and minimize area losses. This piece explores narrative possibilities by ressignifying the tool usage.

Made in Cables.gl

metadata.name: Patched #58
metadata.description:
An attempt at creating realistic looking textures and fabrics using only code. This process just as frustrating and painstaking as actually sewing pieces of material together but resulting in something that has endless iterations but can't be felt or worn and will never wear out. 
4 palettes each with variations in design elements. 
Please see my website for further information about the design process.

metadata.name: Stippled Sketch #271
metadata.description:
Stippled Sketch is an experimental attempt to imitate the result of sitting down and mindlessly finding form on the page. The process of pressing the pen to paper in a rhythmic, repeated pattern can be a form of meditation, much like doodling. 

The form at the center of the sketch can sometimes take a clear and recognizable shape, but it can also appear meandering and meaningless at times. Some forms appear more often than others (such as a clover and circle), but the equation at the core of the algorithm has surprised me quite a few times with unique and unusual shapes, even after reviewing thousands of previews. 

I like to think of this collection as a reflection of a time in my life when I wanted to say so much‚Äîand I could put the pen to the paper, but I knew that no words would have any effect, so I sketched to focus my attention on something else instead.

metadata.name: follow my lead #181
metadata.description:
'follow my lead' is a visualization of three communities of individuals, and the ways in which they interact with each other.

Using an implementation of a physarum slime mold model, I create three distinct groups of homogenous individuals, with each group having different sentiments towards the others. Individuals within a community make their best effort to follow each other around, and depending on group preferences try to either move towards or away from those in other groups.

All of these interactions take place on a simulated three dimensional landscape (that varies by token), with groups of individuals having a preference towards either moving uphill or downhill.

Each group begins with a different spatial distribution, such that the extent of exposure to others can change over time.

For more details on the slime mold implementation and a link to the github repo containing the code, see the accompanying fx(text) article.


Animation
---------
This is designed first as a static piece. The final image consists of running 300 steps of the algorithm and then stopping.

However, I have also exposed a couple of ways to watch the image evolve over time. It should be noted that for some outputs, the image will eventually degenerate as we go well past the initial 300 frames.

Keys:
- space: Pauses/unpauses the animation
- 'F': Fresh start - reloads the page and animates the first 300 frames, pausing when finished (or append &fresh=true to the URL)
- 'A': Animate - reloads the page and animates in perpetuity (or append &animate=true to the URL)

WebGL
-----
This piece makes heavy use of shaders/WebGL. I've put quite a lot of time/effort into trying to ensure things behave identically across different browsers/hardware. I've managed to get things to the point where I was consistently seeing identical outputs on the set of hardware available to me. However, there is still a risk that on other hardware specs, things will not be identical. Furthermore, it is the nature of this project that even very small differences in calculations can become exaggerated after multiple steps of the algorithm, leading to larger differences in the final result.


References:
Jeff Jones's Physarum paper: https://uwe-repository.worktribe.com/output/980579
Sage Jensen's post on Physarum, which was my first exposure to it: https://cargocollective.com/sagejenson/physarum
Color names generated using coloraze: https://github.com/evansque/coloraze
